Search tweets on the topic of your choice. I want to analyze the sentiment around different stock companies $AAPL and $AMC

stock1 <- search_tweets(
  "$AAPL",
  n = 100,
  include_rts = FALSE
)
stock2 <- search_tweets(
  "$AMC",
  n = 100,
  include_rts = FALSE
)

clean up the text by stemming words (removing links, punctuations, making text lowercase and using stop words) stop words are those words that do not help in determining sentiment such as pronouns, articles etc

head(tweets.stock1$text)
## [1] "@NStocks96 I keep waiting for $AAPL to turn around, but doesn't seem like it's happening any time soon? Have they started their stock buy backs yet?"                         
## [2] "Make or break ☠️ $Tsla $Amzn $Aapl $Nflx https://t.co/9W486gDCR8"                                                                                                              
## [3] "Ohhhhh. They went stop hunting on $aapl. Those dirty dogs."                                                                                                                   
## [4] "$AAPL \U0001f913\nWatching ✍\U0001f3fb"                                                                                                                                       
## [5] "@CashApp $Handsomehunnie &amp; Apple $AAPL"                                                                                                                                   
## [6] "$NFLX $SPY $AMC $QQQ $AMD $TSLA $AAPL $NVDA $BABA\n\nGuys, Another great week  i’ve made 5k to $39k after joined this room!!\nhttps://t.co/hDPmHdFE79 https://t.co/MGRMsXKL4s"
#remove links manually
tweets.stock1$stripped_text <- gsub('http\\S+|\\$\\S+', "", tweets.stock1$text)

head(tweets.stock1$stripped_text)
## [1] "@NStocks96 I keep waiting for  to turn around, but doesn't seem like it's happening any time soon? Have they started their stock buy backs yet?"
## [2] "Make or break ☠️     "                                                                                                                           
## [3] "Ohhhhh. They went stop hunting on  Those dirty dogs."                                                                                           
## [4] " \U0001f913\nWatching ✍\U0001f3fb"                                                                                                              
## [5] "@CashApp  &amp; Apple "                                                                                                                         
## [6] "        \n\nGuys, Another great week  i’ve made 5k to  after joined this room!!\n "
# create a token for each word in stripped_text (using unnest_tokens to remove punctuations. By default, to_lower is true)
tweets.stock1_words <- tweets.stock1 %>% select(stripped_text) %>% unnest_tokens(word, stripped_text)

# remove stop words 
tweets.stock1_filtered <- tweets.stock1_words %>% anti_join(stop_words)
## Joining, by = "word"
head(tweets.stock1_filtered)
## # A tibble: 6 x 1
##   word     
##   <chr>    
## 1 nstocks96
## 2 waiting  
## 3 happening
## 4 time     
## 5 started  
## 6 stock

#head(tweets.stock2$text)

#remove links manually
tweets.stock2$stripped_text <- gsub('http\\S+|\\$\\S+', "", tweets.stock2$text)

# create a token for each word in stripped_text (using unnest_tokens to remove punctuations. By default, to_lower is true)
tweets.stock2_words <- tweets.stock2 %>% select(stripped_text) %>% unnest_tokens(word, stripped_text)

# remove stop words 
tweets.stock2_filtered <- tweets.stock2_words %>% anti_join(stop_words)

Let’s find the top 10 used words in both tweets

# Top 10 words in $AAPL tweet
tweets.stock1_filtered %>%
  count(word, sort=TRUE) %>%
  top_n(20) %>%
  mutate(word=reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=word, y=n)) + geom_col() + xlab(NULL) + coord_flip() + theme_classic() + 
  labs(x="Count", y="Unique words", title="Unique words found in $AAPL tweets")
## Selecting by n

# Top 10 words in $AMC tweet

visualize our data

bing_stock1 %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  top_n(20) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(word, n, fill = sentiment)) + geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) + facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales="free_y") + labs(title="Tweets containing $AAPL", x = NULL, y = "contribution to sentiment") + coord_flip() + theme_bw()
## Selecting by n

bing_stock2 %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  top_n(20) %>%
  ungroup() %>%

Let’s visualize the positive and negative words in wordcloud

  acast(word ~ sentiment, value.var = 'n', fill=0) %>%
  comparison.cloud(colors=c("#F8766D", "#00BFC4"),
                   max.words=100)
